Consider the following queries on the [users collection](fts-sort-index)
given an additional document with a multi-typed array in field `c`:```json
db.users.insertOne({
  "_id": 7,
  "a": UUID("03e32aa9-1cbd-43b8-b9d6-18b171a03cc7"),
  "b": "hello",
  "c": [ false, null, 15 ]
})
```The following queries search field `b` for the string `hello`
using the [text](text-ref) operator and sorts the results by field `c`.**Default:**Default> **Note:** Setting `noData: lowest` in your [sort syntax](sort-syntax-ref)
> is the same as the default.**Ascending-sort:**Ascending SortFor an ascending sort, MongoDB Search uses the element with the
lowest BSON (Binary Javascript Object Notation) type to represent the multi-typed array.
By default, MongoDB Search considers null or missing values
as the lowest BSON (Binary Javascript Object Notation) value. Therefore,
MongoDB Search uses `null` to represent the multi-typed array for
the document with `_id: 7` and returns this document at
the top of the results along with other null and missing values.To learn more, see [Sort by Null and Missing Values](fts-sort-null) and
[Sort Arrays with Multiple Types](fts-sort-arrays-multiple-types).**Input:**```json
db.users.aggregate([
  {
    "$search": {
      "text": {
        "path": "b",
        "query": "hello"
      },
      "sort": {
        "c": 1
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "$project": {
      "_id": 1,
      "c": 1,
      "score": { "$meta": "searchScore" }
    }
  }
])
```**Output:**```js
[
  { _id: 4, c: null, score: 0.025981096550822258 },
  { _id: 5, c: [], score: 0.025981096550822258 },
  { _id: 6, score: 0.025981096550822258 }
  { _id: 7, c: [ false, null, 15 ], score: 0.025981096550822258 },
  { _id: 2, c: 'foo', score: 0.025981096550822258 },
  {
    _id: 3,
    c: UUID('3be11d4e-62cb-4e95-9a3c-5c9f1e56c732'),
